```json
{
"application": "PBS",
"software": [
"PrgEnv-intel",
"craype",
"intel",
"cray-mpich",
"hdf5",
"netcdf",
"pnetcdf",
"prod_util",
"wgrib2",
"util_shared",
"cray-pals",
"envvar"
],
"resources": {
"cpus": 128,
"walltime": "00:15:00",
"queue": "dev",
"account": "HRRR-DEV",
"OMP_NUM_THREADS": 1,
"MP_TASK_AFFINITY": "core:1",
"KMP_AFFINITY": "disabled",
"MP_MPILIB": "mpich2",
"NWROOT": "/lfs/h2/emc/lam/noscrub/Benjamin.Blake/nwprod",
"DATAROOT": "/lfs/h2/emc/ptmp/Benjamin.Blake"
}
}
```

The script is running on a PBS (Portable Batch System) cluster. It requires a total of 128 CPUs and a walltime of 15 minutes. The script utilizes a specific set of software modules, including various Intel, Cray, and HDF5 libraries, along with utilities like `prod_util` and `wgrib2`. The script also sets environment variables like `NWROOT`, `DATAROOT`, and MPI settings. It executes the `JHRRR_MAKEGUESS` executable job script, which is likely a part of the HRRR (High-Resolution Rapid Refresh) model, and then submits multiple other jobs related to data preparation using `qsub`.
